A stray adult male horse (H14) restrained at the U.S. – Mexico border (Eagle Pass, Texas) was hypothesized to be infected with T. equi based on a borderline positive result (42% inhibition) in a cELISA (Knowles et al., 1992) (VMRD, Inc., catalog #274.2). Blood-transfer from H14 to a naive splenectomized horse, H208(S), resulted in a parasitemia detectable by light microscopy. Intra-erythrocytic parasite morphology was consistent with Theileria and 18S rDNA sequencing placed this Theileria parasite within a different clade than T. equi
                        FL and T. equi™, isolates from Florida and Texas, respectively (Fig. 1
                        ). Four additional horses, one located in Mexico (N), one in Georgia(C), one in Texas(S), and one in Florida(S) were shown to be infected with this same undescribed species, according to the sequence of the 18S rDNA locus (Supplementary Table S1). The letter in parenthesis following each state is a horse identifier. Detailed phylogenetic analyses based on 18S rDNA and nuclear-encoded protein-coding genes confirm the placement of this parasite within the genus Theileria, and show it to be most closely related to Theileria parasites isolated from the waterbuck (Kobus defassa) and from African equids including the South African mountain zebra. The 18S rDNA and genome sequence data also reveal the exceptional genetic diversity present within Theileria that are infective to equids, which will complicate detection of ‘cryptic’ parasites that may be important, particularly in the context of coinfections (Woolhouse et al., 2015).

Both phylogenetic and synteny analyses support the hypothesis that the ema family underwent expansion prior to the speciation event that led to separation of the lineages leading to the emergence of T. equi
                        FL and T. haneyi n. sp. as distinct taxa. This hypothesis is supported by the fact that six of the copies have clear orthologs in the two species (Fig. 3
                        ). The EMA genes ema1, ema3 and ema4, all located on chromosome 1 in T. equi, have no detectable orthologs in T. haneyi n. sp. The absence of ema1 in T. haneyi n. sp. partially explains the inability to detect T. haneyi n. sp. infection with current T. equi diagnostics based on an EMA-1 epitope (cELISA) and ema1 sequence (PCR), indicating the need for a combined T. equi and T. haneyi n. sp. diagnostic test. The cELISA data (Supplementary Fig. S2) indicates that EMA-2 within T. haneyi n. sp. also does not possess the epitope bound by monoclonal antibody (mAb)133.97. Since, as indicated by the phylogenetic analysis, ema3, ema4 and possibly ema1 predate the origin of other ema copies with orthologs in both species, ema3, ema4 and possibly ema1 must have been present in the common ancestor of the two species, and were subsequently lost in T. haneyi n. sp. (Fig. 3). Theileria haneyi n. sp. contains three distinct emas, named ema11-13, two located on chromosome 1, in non-syntenic positions relative to ema1, ema3 and ema4, and one on chromosome 2. Phylogenetic and sequence similarity evidence suggest that the three unique T. haneyi n. sp. ema genes resulted from species-specific duplication and inter-chromosomal insertion events. The three genes are each other’s closest relatives and share higher amino acid sequence identity with each other (74–81%) than to other ema family members in either species (50–54%). However, since these comparisons are only based on analyses of one genome from each species, the ema gene differences reported here between T. equi and T. haneyi n. sp. cannot be assumed to be diagnostic for each species. While it is hypothesized that EMA alleles within T. equi or T. haneyi n. sp. are less divergent than the orthologues, data is required from within each species to confirm this.

Phylogenetic analysis of the 18S rDNA locus, as well as genome sequence and organization, all suggest a novel parasite species, designated here T. haneyi n. sp. A comparison of 1,320 orthologous genes between T. equi
                        FL and T. haneyi n. sp. revealed an average amino acid sequence divergence of 23%, higher than the 18% observed between T. parva and T. annulata for the orthologous proteins (Fig. 4
                        ). We used these data to estimate the divergence time between T. equi
                        FL and T. haneyi n. sp. using the approach of Silva and colleagues (Silva et al., 2015). The phylogenetic placement of T. haneyi n. sp. was confirmed using ∼220 protein-coding genes predicted by GeneMark-ES using single copy homologs across five species of Theileria (including T. haneyi n. sp.) and four species of Babesia. In this analysis, T. haneyi is the sister taxon to T. equi
                        FL, and together they form a clade sister to the one containing T. parva and T. annulata (Fig. 5
                        ).

The age of the MRCA of T. parva and T. annulata was estimated relative to the age of the MRCA of T. haneyi n. sp. and T. equi
                        FL using TLS regression (Silva et al., 2015). A simple protein molecular clock model provided a good fit to the data, explaining approximately 47% of the variation in the data (Fig. 6
                        ). The slope of the TLS regression between protein divergence in the two species pairs indicates that the speciation event leading to T. parva and T. annulata is approximately three-fourths (0.77) the age of the split between T. equi and T. haneyi n. sp. The absolute age of the split between T. parva and T. annulata can be estimated by calibrating nucleotide divergence in synonymous sites between the two species (median d
                        S = 0.765) with the rate of synonymous substitution per site per year estimated for metazoans (∼8.1 × 10−9) and for invertebrates (1.5 × 10−8). Accordingly, T. parva and T. annulata last shared a common ancestor between 25.5 and 47.3 million years ago (mya), which places the MRCA of T. haneyi n. sp. and T. equi at approximately 33 to 61 mya (Table 2
                        ).
